                >+</span
              >
            </summary>
            <div
              class="mt-4 text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed"
              itemscope
              itemprop="acceptedAnswer"
              itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"
            >
              <p itemprop="text">
                While inspiration is subjective, Brené Brown's "The power of
                vulnerability" is widely cited as the most inspiring TED talk,
                helping millions embrace vulnerability and build stronger
                connections. Other highly inspiring talks include Mel Robbins'
                "How to stop screwing yourself over" and Robert Waldinger's
                study on what makes a good life.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group py-6"
            itemscope
            itemprop="mainEntity"
            itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <h3
                class="text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wide text-black group-open:text-[#EB0028] transition-colors"
                itemprop="name"
              >
                Are TED Talks scripted or unscripted?
              </h3>
              <span
                class="text-[#EB0028] text-xl font-light ml-4 group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform"
                >+</span
              >
            </summary>
            <div
              class="mt-4 text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed"
              itemscope
              itemprop="acceptedAnswer"
              itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"
            >
              <p itemprop="text">
                TED talks are highly scripted, structured, and rigorously
                prepared. Speakers work closely with TED's editorial team and
                speech coaches for months before the event to refine their
                message. While talks are designed to feel natural and
                conversational, every word, slide, and movement is usually
                planned, memorized, and rehearsed.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details
            class="group py-6"
            itemscope
            itemprop="mainEntity"
            itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"
          >
            <summary
              class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer list-none"
            >
              <h3
                class="text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wide text-black group-open:text-[#EB0028] transition-colors"
                itemprop="name"
              >
                What is the longest Ted talk ever?
              </h3>
              <span
                class="text-[#EB0028] text-xl font-light ml-4 group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform"
                >+</span
              >
            </summary>
            <div
              class="mt-4 text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed"
              itemscope
              itemprop="acceptedAnswer"
              itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"
            >
              <p itemprop="text">
                Official main-stage TED talks are strictly limited to 18
                minutes, though some older talks (like E.O. Wilson's in 2007)
                ran slightly longer at 22-23 minutes. In contrast, local,
                independently organized TEDx events can sometimes feature longer
                talks or panel discussions, but the 18-minute rule remains the
                golden standard for TED.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

